We may consider the diameter of circle $C$ as the base of the inscribed triangle; its length is $20\text{ cm}$. Then the corresponding height extends from some point on the diameter to some point on the circle $C$. The greatest possible height is a radius of $C$, achieved when the triangle is right isosceles: [asy]
unitsize(8);
draw(Circle((0,0),10));
draw(((-10,0)--(10,0)));
label("$20$",(0,0),S);
draw(((-10,-0.8)--(-0.8,-0.6)),BeginArrow);
draw(((0.8,-0.8)--(10,-0.8)),EndArrow);
draw(((-10,0)--(0,10)));
draw(((0,10)--(10,0)));
draw(((0,0)--(0,10)),dashed);
label("$10$",(0,2.5),E);
[/asy] In this case, the height is $10\text{ cm}$, so the area of the triangle is $$\frac 12\cdot 20\cdot 10 = \boxed{100}\text{ square centimeters}.$$

The surface area of a cylinder with radius $r$ and height $h$ is $2\pi r^2+2\pi rh$.  Setting this expression equal to $112\pi$ and substituting $h=2.5r$ gives  \begin{align*}
2\pi r(r+2.5r) &= 112\pi \\
7\pi r^2 &= 112\pi \\
r^2 &= 16 \\
r&=\boxed{4} \text{ cm}.
\end{align*}

