solution:
Note that $\angle AOC = 180^\circ - 50^\circ = 130^\circ$.  Because triangle $AOC$ is isosceles, $\angle CAB = (180^\circ - 130^\circ)/2 = \boxed{25^\circ}$.

[asy]
import graph;

unitsize(2 cm);

pair O, A, B, C;

O = (0,0);
A = (-1,0);
B = (1,0);
C = dir(50);

draw(Circle(O,1));
draw(B--A--C--O);

label("$A$", A, W);
label("$B$", B, E);
label("$C$", C, NE);
label("$O$", O, S);
[/asy]

We will calculate the area of the hexagon in two different ways.  Let the interior point in the figure be called $P$, and let $s$ be the side length of the hexagon. The areas of the triangles $APB$, $BPC$, $CPD$, $DPE$, $EPF$, and $FPA$ are $\frac{1}{2}(s)(4)$, $\frac{1}{2}(s)(6)$, $\frac{1}{2}(s)(9)$, $\frac{1}{2}(s)(10)$, $\frac{1}{2}(s)(8)$, and $\frac{1}{2}(s)(5)$, respectively.  Also, the area of a regular hexagon with side length $s$ is $3s^2\sqrt{3}/2$.  Setting the sum of the triangles' areas equal to $3s^2\sqrt{3}/2$ gives \begin{align*}
\frac{1}{2}s(4 + 6 + 9 + 10 + 8 + 5)&=\frac{3s^2\sqrt{3}}{2} \implies \\
21s&=\frac{3s^2\sqrt{3}}{2} \implies \\
14s &= s^2\sqrt{3} \implies \\
s=0 \quad \text{or} \quad s &= \frac{14}{\sqrt{3}} \\
&= \frac{14}{\sqrt{3}}\cdot\frac{\sqrt{3}}{\sqrt{3}}=\boxed{\frac{14\sqrt{3}}{3}} \text{ cm}.
\end{align*}[asy]
unitsize(0.3 cm);

pair A, B, C, D, E, F, P, U, V, W, X, Y, Z;

A = 14*sqrt(3)/3*dir(60);
B = 14*sqrt(3)/3*dir(120);
C = 14*sqrt(3)/3*dir(180);
D = 14*sqrt(3)/3*dir(240);
E = 14*sqrt(3)/3*dir(300);
F = 14*sqrt(3)/3*dir(360);
P = extension(A + (0,-4), B + (0,-4), A + 5*dir(210), F + 5*dir(210));

U = (P + reflect(A,B)*(P))/2;
V = (P + reflect(B,C)*(P))/2;
W = (P + reflect(C,D)*(P))/2;
X = (P + reflect(D,E)*(P))/2;
Y = (P + reflect(E,F)*(P))/2;
Z = (P + reflect(F,A)*(P))/2;

draw(A--B--C--D--E--F--cycle);
draw(U--X,dotted);
draw(V--Y,dotted);
draw(W--Z,dotted);
draw(A--P);
draw(B--P);
draw(C--P);
draw(D--P);
draw(E--P);
draw(F--P);

label("$A$", A, dir(60));
label("$B$", B, dir(120));
label("$C$", C, dir(180));
label("$D$", D, dir(240));
label("$E$", E, dir(300));
label("$F$", F, dir(360));
label("$P$", P, SW, UnFill);
label("$4$", (P + U)/2, dir(180));
label("$6$", (P + V)/2, SW);
label("$9$", (P + W)/2, SE);
label("$10$", (P + X)/2, dir(180));
label("$8$", (P + Y)/2, SW);
label("$5$", (P + Z)/2, SE);
[/asy]

[asy]
import three;
triple A = (4,8,0);
triple B= (4,0,0);
triple C = (0,0,0);
triple D = (0,8,0);
triple P = (4,8,6);
draw(B--P--D--A--B);
draw(A--P);
draw(A--C--P, dashed);
draw(B--C--D,dashed);
label("$A$",A,S);
label("$B$",B,W);
label("$C$",C,S);
label("$D$",D,E);
label("$P$",P,N);
[/asy]

Since $\overline{PA}$ is perpendicular to both $\overline{AB}$ and $\overline{AD}$, the segment $\overline{PA}$ is the altitude from the apex to the base of the pyramid.   Applying the Pythagorean Theorem to triangle $ABC$ gives us $AC = \sqrt{13}$.  Applying the Pythagorean Theorem to triangle $PAC$ gives us $PA = \sqrt{PC^2 - AC^2} = \sqrt{12} = 2\sqrt{3}$.

The area of the base of the pyramid is $[ABCD] = (AB)(BC) = 6$, so the volume of the pyramid is $\frac13(6)(2\sqrt{3}) = \boxed{4\sqrt{3}}$ cubic units.

