Square $ABCD$ has side length 2. A semicircle with diameter $\overline{AB}$ is constructed inside the square, and the tangent to the semicircle from $C$ intersects side $\overline{AD}$ at $E$. What is the length of $\overline{CE}$?

[asy]
pair A,B,C,D,I;
I=(0,2.5);
A=(0,0);
B=(10,0);
C=(10,10);
D=(0,10);
draw((5,5)..A--B..cycle,linewidth(0.7));
draw(C--I,linewidth(0.7));
draw(A--B--C--D--cycle,linewidth(0.7));
label("$A$",A,SW);
label("$B$",B,SE);
label("$C$",C,NE);
label("$D$",D,NW);
label("$E$",I,W);
[/asy]

solution:
Let $F$ be the point at which $\overline{CE}$ is tangent to the semicircle, and let $G$ be the midpoint of $\overline{AB}$.  Because $\overline{CF}$ and $\overline{CB}$ are both tangents to the semicircle, $CF = CB = 2$.  Similarly, $EA =
EF$.  Let $x = AE$.  The Pythagorean Theorem applied to $\triangle
CDE$ gives \[
(2-x)^{2}+ 2^{2}= (2+x)^{2}.
\]It follows that $x= 1/2$ and $CE = 2 + x= \boxed{\frac{5}{2}}$.

[asy]
pair A,B,C,D,I;
I=(0,2.5);
A=(0,0);
B=(10,0);
C=(10,10);
D=(0,10);
draw((5,5)..A--B..cycle,linewidth(0.7));
draw(C--I,linewidth(0.7));
draw(A--B--C--D--cycle,linewidth(0.7));
label("$A$",A,SW);
label("$B$",B,SE);
label("$C$",C,NE);
label("$D$",D,NW);
label("$E$",I,W);
label("$F$",(2,4),NW);
label("$G$",(5,0),S);
draw((5,0)--C,dashed);
draw((5,0)--(2,4),dashed);
draw((5,0)--I,dashed);
[/asy]

problem:
In the diagram, $K$, $O$ and $M$ are the centers of the three semi-circles. Also, $OC = 32$ and $CB = 36$.

[asy]
pair A, K, O, C, M, B, X, Y, Z;
O=(0,0);
C=(32,0);
M=(50,0);
B=(68,0);
A=(-68,0);
K=(A+C)/2;
X=(0,68);
Y=(-18,50);
Z=(50,18);
path nom, bigc, middlec, smallc;
nom=A--B--(100,100)--(-100,100)--cycle;
bigc=A..X..B--cycle;
middlec=A..Y..C--cycle;
smallc=C..Z..B--cycle;
fill(bigc, gray(.5));
fill(middlec, white);
fill(smallc, white);
draw(smallc);
draw(middlec);
draw(bigc);
